dden Anti-David Polemic in 2 Samuel 6:2 -- tThe Prophet and the Augur at Tušḫan, 611 b.c. -- tAssyria and Judean Identity: Beyond the Religionsgeschichtliche Schule -- tPsalm 22:16 and Its Sumerian and Akkadian Analogues -- tDo Ideas Travel Lightly?: Early Greek Concepts of Justice in Their Mediterranean Context -- tThe Rod that Smote Philistia: Isaiah 14:28-32 -- tErrant Oxen Or: The Goring Ox Redux -- tJephthah: Chutzpah and Overreach in a Hebrew Judge -- tThe Remembrance of Kings Past: The Persona of King Ibbi-Sin -- tHittite Gods in Egyptian Attire: A Case Study in Cultural Transmission -- tHow Did Šulgi and Išbi-Erra Ascend to Heaven? -- t"War Crimes" in Amos's Oracles Against the Nations (Amos 1:3-2:3) -- tGrammar and Context: Enki & Ninhursag ll. 1-3 and a Rare Sumerian Construction -- tTowards a Biography of Kish: Notes on Urbanism and Comparison -- tIndex of Authors -- tIndex of Scripture0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume, in celebration of Peter Machinist, Hancock Professor of Hebrew and Other Oriental Languages at Harvard University, includes twenty-eight illuminating essays on ancient Near Eastern history and literature, which focus especially on the intersection of these fields. Contributors include one of Machinist's teachers, several of his students, and numerous colleagues and friends. These essays probe topics for which Machinist's work has often set new standards. And in the spirit of the honoree and his interests, these comparative studies encompass Babel, Bibel, and more. In them, Assyriologists contend with biblical cruxes and biblicists engage Assyriological research, while classicists and Hittitologists participate with considerations of their respective disciplines within a broad cross-cultural context. The volume is a must for anyone committed to the ongoing comparative study of the ancient Near East, and within that framework, the historical study of the Hebrew Bible.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aAvigdor Hurowitz, Victor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Yoram, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDubovský, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFales, Frederick Mario, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFleming, Daniel E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrahm, Eckart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlassner, Jean-Jacques, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldstein, Ronnie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHallo, William W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalpern, Baruch, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamilton, Mark W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuddlestun, John R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiverani, Mario, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMichalowski, Piotr, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNaʾaman, Nadav, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNissinen, Martti, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOtto, Eckart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaul, Shalom M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaaflaub, Kurt A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoberts, J. J. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoth, Martha T